white Knight in simply hastens the end.} 17. Nxe6 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Yg5e6] Our
Queen pockets a second pawn and her Knight now has more threats -} (17. Nxe6 {
[%csl Rc5,Rc7,Rg7][%cal Ye6c7,Ye6c5,Ye6g7]}) 17... Kf7 {[%cal Ye8f7]} 18. Bb3
$1 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Ya4b3,Yb3f7] Setting up an x-ray on the now exposed black
King.} h4 $2 {[%cal Yh5h4] Still refusing to develop the queenside pieces and
ignoring White's threats.} 19. Nc7+ {[%csl Ra8,Rf7][%cal Yc7a8,Yb3f7] This
discovered attack picks off the black Rook in the a8 corner.} c4 {[%cal Yc5c4]
This interposition simply tosses another pawn onto the bonfire.} 20. Bxc4+ {
[%csl Gc4,Rf7][%cal Yb3c4,Yc4f7]} Kg6 {[%cal Yf7g6]} 21. Nxa8 {[%csl Ga8][%cal
Yc7a8] +10.00 White has a huge material advantage and will rescue her Knight
and then turn her attention to the black King.} Bb7 {[%csl Ra8,Re4][%cal Yc8b7,
Yb7a8,Yb7e4] Finally, after the game has been decided, Black develops a
queenside piece with a double attack on a8 and e4.} 22. Nc7 {[%cal Ya8c7]} Bxe4
{[%csl Ge4][%cal Ya8e4]} 23. Rhe1 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Yh1e1,Ye1e4] White, even
a ton of material ahead, focuses on completing the mobilization of her forces.
The white Rook on h1 was the only unit not developed.} ({Note how all of the
white forces are devloped in the center -} 23. Rhe1 {[%csl Gc4,Gc7,Gd1,Gd6,Ge1]
}) 23... Bxg2 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Ye4g2] With his Bishop under attack, Black
figures since he has to protect it or move it, he might as well at least grab
a pawn. However, he simply walks into a pin along the g-file.} 24. Rg1 $1 $18 {
[%csl Gg1,Rg2,Rg6][%cal Ye1g1,Yg1g2,Yg2g6] +15.00. White makes immediate use
of the newly half opened g-file to pin the black Bishop to his King.} 1-0

