1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 a6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. h3 $5 {Perhaps theoretically not the
most accurate move for White, but creating a "Hidey Hole" on h2 for the dark
square Bishop takes the worry away from White about any Nf6-h5 action by Black.
} ({FRITZ prefers} 5. Nc3 {but I don't see the point in blocking in the white
c-pawn.}) ({A London player might consider -} 5. Bd3 $5 c5 6. c3 {leading to a
typical London System.}) 5... Be7 (5... Nh5 6. Bh2) 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. Bd3 Nc6 $6 {
Blocking in the black c-pawn inhibits Black's chances of creating counterplay
against the white queenside.} 8. c3 ({White has completed his "Stonewall Pawn
Formation" -} 8. c3 {[%csl Gb2,Gc3,Gd4,Ge3,Gf2]}) 8... Bd6 9. Ne5 $5 Ne8 (9...
Ne8 {Black envisions kicking the white Knight out of e5 with his f-pawn -} 10.
Z0 f6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Yf7f6,Rf6e5]}) (9... Nxe5 10. dxe5) (9... Bxe5 10. Bxe5
(10. dxe5 Nd7 11. Nf3) 10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7 12. f4) 10. Qh5 $5 (10. Qc2 $5 {
[%csl Rh7][%cal Yc2d3,Rd3h7,Yd1c2]}) (10. Qh5 Z0 11. Qxh7# {[%csl Rg8,Gh7]
[%cal Rh7g8,Yh5h7]}) 10... f5 {Black blocks the d3-h7 diagonal with his f-pawn,
but now the f5 pawn can be used as a hook for White to open kingside files
with.} (10... Nf6 11. Qe2) (10... h6 11. O-O $16) (10... g6 11. Qe2 $16) 11.
O-O-O $5 {Knowing he will be able to use the g2-g4 pawn break to force open
the kingside, White feels comfortable castling queenside. In addition, the
blocked in black c-pawn impedes Black's usual queenside counterplay.} Nf6 12.
Qe2 Ne7 $6 13. g4 Ng6 14. Bh2 $16 Ne7 $6 15. Rdg1 $36 c5 16. dxc5 $5 {[%csl
Gc5]} Bxc5 {[%csl Gc5]} 17. Nb3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Yb3c5]} Bd6 18. Nd4 (18. Nd4 {
[%csl Gd4,Ge5]}) 18... Bxe5 $2 {[%csl Ge5]} 19. Bxe5 {[%csl Ge5]} Nc6 {[%csl
Re5][%cal Yc6e5,Ye7c6]} 20. Nxc6 $5 {[%csl Gc6] White exchanges Knights in
order to maintain his Bishop on e5.} bxc6 {[%csl Gc6]} 21. gxf5 {[%csl Gf5]
[%cal Yg1g7,Yg7g8] White finally get the g-file half opened.} exf5 {[%csl Gf5]}
22. Rg5 {[%cal Yh1g1,Yg1g5] White begins to double on the g file.} Qe7 {
[%csl Re5][%cal Re7e5,Yd8e7]} 23. f4 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yf4e5,Yf2f4]} ({White
anchors his monster dark square Bishop in on the e5 outpost -} 23. f4 {[%csl
Ge5][%cal Ye5d6,Yd6c7,Yc7b8,Ye5f6,Yf6g7]}) 23... Ne4 $2 {Simply allowing White
to crash through on g7.} ({A bit better was trying some lateral defense to
shore up the g7 pawn -} 23... Rf7 24. Rhg1 a5 25. a4 Ra7 {even so, White can
break through with} 26. Bxf5 $1 h6 27. Bxc8 hxg5 28. Rxg5 Ne4 29. Rg6 $18 {
[%csl Rc6,Re6][%cal Yg6c6,Yc8e6,Ye6f7,Yf7g8] When White's Bishop Pair and pawn
more than compensate for the sacrificed exchange.}) 24. Bxe4 {[%csl Ge4]} dxe4
{[%csl Ge4]} 25. Qc4+ $5 {[%csl Yg8][%cal Yc4g8]} ({Of course White could have
played the expected capture on g7 -} 25. Rxg7+ {[%csl Re7,Gg7,Rg8][%cal Rg7e7,
Rg7g8,Yg5g7]} Qxg7 {[%csl Gg7]} 26. Bxg7 $18 {[%csl Gg7]}) 25... Be6 {[%csl
Rc4][%cal Ye6c4]} 26. Rxg7+ {[%csl Gg7,Rg8][%cal Yg7g8,Yg5g7]} Qxg7 {[%csl Gg7]
} 27. Qxe6+ $1 {[%csl Ge6,Rg8][%cal Re6g8,Yc4e6]} Qf7 (27... Rf7 28. Bxg7 {
[%csl Gg7]} Kxg7 {[%csl Gg7]} 29. Rg1+ {[%csl Gg1,Rg7][%cal Rg1g7,Yh1g1]} Kf8
30. Qd6+ {[%csl Gd6,Rf8][%cal Yd6f8] mate in 13.}) 28. Rg1# {[%csl Gg1,Rg8]
[%cal Yh1g1,Rg1g8]} 1-0

