{In 1922 London organized the British Chess Federation Congresswhich was won
by the Third World Champion Jose Raul Capablanca with an undefeated score of
13 points out of 15. A very impressive performance indeed considering such
legends as Alekhine, Rubinstein, Vidmar, Reti, Euwe, Bogoljubow and Maroczy
among others. From our perspective what is more important was the previously
named "Mason Variation", the opening system with 1.d4 d5 2.Bf4 was quite
popular in the tournament and as a result became known as the "London System".
In this illustrative game, the strongest player to never become World Champion
Akiba Rubinstein unveils an original strategic plan. He allows his f-pawns to
become doubled, but in return gains dark square control and in particular a
clamp on the e5 square. The fact this was played against a savvy verteran like
TArtakower makes it all the more impressive and important.} 1. d4 {[%cal Yd2d4]
} Nf6 {[%cal Yg8f6]} 2. Nf3 {[%cal Yg1f3]} d5 {[%cal Yd7d5]} 3. Bf4 {[%cal
Yc1f4]} e6 {[%cal Ye7e6]} 4. e3 {[%cal Ye2e3]} Bd6 {[%cal Yf8d6]} 5. Nbd2 $5 {
[%cal Yb1d2] Rubinstein's original idea is to allow doubled f-pawns and clamp
down on the dark squares.  The alternative responses are -} ({a)} 5. Bg3 {
[%cal Yf4g3]} Bxg3 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Yd6g3]} 6. hxg3 {[%cal Yh2g3,Yh1h7]}) ({b)
} 5. Bxd6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Yf4d6]} cxd6 $5 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Yc7d6]}) 5... Bxf4
{[%csl Gf4][%cal Yd6f4]} 6. exf4 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Ye3f4]} (6. exf4 {[%csl Gd4,
Ge5,Gf2,Gf4][%cal Yf4e5,Yd4e5]}) 6... c5 {[%cal Yc7c5] Possibly premature.} ({
A smoother strategic plan was} 6... O-O {[%cal Ye8g8]} 7. Bd3 {[%cal Yf1d3]} b6
$5 {[%cal Yb7b6] with plans of} 8. Z0 Ba6 {[%cal Yc8a6]} (8... c5 {[%cal Yc7c5]
})) 7. dxc5 $5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Yd4c5]} ({After} 7. c3 {[%cal Yc2c3]} cxd4 {
