Rubinstein introduces the idea of allowing Black to capture on f4 and then
uses the doubled f-pawns to clamp down on the e5 square.  2) With 7.dxc5, 10.
c3 and 12.Nb3, Rubinstein assumes control of the d4 central outpost.  3) An
early example of the advancing white h-pawn gaining kingside space and
crimping the black g-pawn.  4) Preparation and execution of the strategic
g3-g4 pawn break by White is worth noting.} 1-0

